From this data  <Document input here>

Role: Strategy Visualizer
Goal: Create a clean "Slope Chart" comparing two periods.

Data Extraction Protocol:

Primary Method: Scan PDF for "Year over Year" or "2024 vs 2025" comparisons across categories.

Fallback Method: Use Demo Data:

Categories: ['Organic', 'Paid Search', 'Referral', 'Social']

Start Values: [20, 40, 30, 10]

End Values: [50, 25, 35, 20]

Step 1: The Canvas

Initialize fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6)).

Create ax_main covering [0,0,1,1] and turn it off.

Draw white card background.

Step 2: The Chart Layer (Centered)

Create axis: ax_chart = fig.add_axes([0.2, 0.2, 0.6, 0.6]) (Leaves 20% margin on both sides).

Nuclear Clean-Up: ax_chart.axis('off').

Vertical Anchors: Draw two thin grey vertical lines at x=0 and x=1 to represent the two time periods.

Step 3: Plotting (The Slopes)

Loop through each category.

Color Logic: If End > Start (Growth) use Brand Blue (#0078D4). If End < Start (Decline) use Light Grey (#E0E0E0).

Lines: Plot line from (0, start_val) to (1, end_val) with linewidth=3, marker='o'.

Step 4: Labels (The "Gutter" Strategy)

Left Side (Start):

Place text at x=-0.05.

ax_chart.text(-0.05, start_val, f"{cat} {start_val}%", ha='right', va='center', fontsize=11, color='grey').

Right Side (End):

Place text at x=1.05.

ax_chart.text(1.05, end_val, f"{end_val}%", ha='left', va='center', fontsize=11, weight='bold', color='black').

Step 5: Text Elements

Title (Top Left): ax_main.text(0.05, 0.90, "Channel Mix Shift (Year 1 vs Year 2)", Size 16, Bold).

Narrative (Bottom): ax_main.text(0.05, 0.10, "Insight: Organic traffic overtook Paid Search as the primary driver.", Size 12).

Final Output:
Do NOT save the file to disk or use file streaming. Do NOT use plt.show(). Instead, perform exactly these steps: 1. Save the figure to a io.BytesIO buffer. 2. Encode that buffer to a Base64 string. 3. Return a JSON object with a "files" list containing the filename, content_type "image/png", and the base64_content string. Return the JSON object only. Do NOT generate a Markdown image link (like ![Image](data:...)) in the text response. Do not output the Base64 string in plain text."
